Amendments to the Sex Discrimination Act which will likely force Australian legal aid programs to fund abortions have been reported by the media as set to proceed through the parliamentam. They are also the subject of widespread controversy which has intensified over the past few days.

A Sunday age poll, published on the 1st of April, had the lead, “History likely to favour women.” One reason given for this, was:

“The high number of women and children affected by the deaths of their partners in the Iraq wars and the Afghanistan conflicts has intensified the concern about care for civilians following military onslaught.”

The issue the article appears to be referring to is the arguments for and against various apologies therefore made, described in Mary Anne Jebb’s article in the *scroll* on some less recognisable “faceless men,”

http://sydney.edu.au/scroll/issue_2_3.shtml#men. The deaths of civilians are not meant to be the only issue here. Of course a military offensive involves many groans and grunts of arm and body everywhere, both fully informed and reluctant, and therefore involves the outright killing of young men and women who were once soldiers in like mood, and who are now casualties and grieving and nursing in some cases the horrible wounds of a recent battle which were inflicted on them by means of a tallying of success as per level of injury.
